      summary: 'Mushroom poisoning varies from mild GI symptoms to fatal liver failure. Delayed onset (>6 hours) suggests amatoxin poisoning with potential mortality. Early GI symptoms usually indicate less dangerous toxins. Poison center consultation is essential.',
      explanation: `## Categories of Mushroom Poisoning

### Early Onset (<6 hours) - Usually Less Severe
- GI irritants (most common)
- Muscarine (sweating, salivation)
- Psilocybin (hallucinations)
- Usually self-limited

### Delayed Onset (>6 hours) - Potentially Deadly
- Amatoxin (death cap) - liver failure
- Gyromitra - liver and CNS toxicity
- Orellanine - kidney failure (days to weeks)

## Warning Signs of Serious Poisoning
- Onset >6 hours after ingestion
- Severe, persistent vomiting/diarrhea
- Jaundice (yellowing)
- Confusion
- Decreased urination

## Management
- Call Poison Control immediately
- Save mushroom sample if possible
- Early GI symptoms (<6 hours): supportive care
- Late symptoms (>6 hours): emergency evaluation
- Amatoxin: liver transplant may be needed

## Prevention
- Never eat unidentified wild mushrooms
- Expert identification only
- Apps and books alone are insufficient`,
